'''François Ngeze''' (born in [[Bujumbura Province]])<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=wr1yAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Francois+Ngeze+(21+October+1993+%E2%80%94+22+October+1993)+was+born+in+Bujumbura+Province+************%22&dq=%22Francois+Ngeze+(21+October+1993+%E2%80%94+22+October+1993)+was+born+in+Bujumbura+Province+************%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5bELT9WxOLCOigLv5NiTBA&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA]</ref> was the [[List of Presidents of Burundi|head of state]] of [[Burundi]] from 21 October 1993 to 27 October 1993.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/24/world/troops-in-burundi-seek-amnesty.html?pagewanted=1|title=Troops in Burundi Seek Amnesty |date=October 24, 1993|work=The New York Times|page =110 |accessdate=3 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72196678.html?dids=72196678:72196678&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+23%2C+1993&author=&pub=The+Washington+Post+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=Crisis+in+Burundi&pqatl=google|title=Crisis in Burundi|date=October 23, 1993 |work=The Washington Post|page =A.18 |accessdate=3 February 2010}}</ref> He was chosen by the military Committee of Public Salvation, a group of army officers that overthrew the democratically elected government of president [[Melchior Ndadaye]] (who was killed during the [[coup]]).

Ngeze, one of the few prominent [[Hutu]] members of UPRONA ([[Union for National Progress]]) at the time, was [[interior minister]] in the government of [[Pierre Buyoya]], who was defeated by Ndadaye in elections held on 1 June 1993.

Following widespread condemnation of the coup, the Committee of Public Salvation was dissolved on 27 October. [[Sylvie Kinigi]], [[Heads of Government of Burundi|prime minister]] in the Ndadaye government, took over as acting president.

