'''Hans Holzer''' (26 January 1920 &ndash; 26 April 2009)<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite news|title=Hans Holzer, Ghost Hunter, Dies at 89|first=William|last=Grimes|date=April 29, 2009|accessdate=April 30, 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/30/books/30holzer.html}}</ref> was an American [[Parapsychology|paranormal researcher]] and author. He wrote more than 120 books on supernatural and occult subjects for the popular market as well as several plays, musicals, films, and documentaries, and hosted a television show, ''Ghost Hunter'' (not to be confused with ''[[Ghost Hunters (TV series)|Ghost Hunters]]'').

==Life and career==
Holzer was born in Vienna, Austria, the son of Martha (Stransky) and Leo Holzer, a businessman.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=L25ycEzuXxIC&pg=PA942&lpg=PA942&dq=Martha+Stransky+Leo+Holzer&source=bl&ots=lmxvl-McD9&sig=e8dB6fn2j-2xylExsXceTv20064&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_kL7D4fXaAhVK04MKHRDxBTAQ6AEIJDAH]</ref> His interest in the supernatural was sparked at a young age by stories told to him by his uncle Henry. He went on to study archaeology and ancient history at the [[University of Vienna]] but seeing that war was imminent, his family decided it was unsafe to stay in Austria and left the country for [[New York City]] in 1938. He studied Japanese at [[Columbia University]] and, after studying comparative religion and parapsychology, claimed to have obtained a [[Ph.D.]] at a school called the London College of Applied Science. He went on to teach parapsychology at the [[New York Institute of Technology]]. Holzer wrote more than 120 books on ghosts and the afterlife.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/jun/18/obituary-hans-holzer Hans Holzer Obituary in The Guardian]</ref>

His extensive involvement in researching the supernatural included investigating [[The Amityville Horror]] and some of the most prominent haunted locations around the world.<ref name=NYTObit/> He also worked with well-known trance [[Mediumship|mediums]] such as [[Ethel Johnson-Meyers]], [[Sybil Leek]], and [[Marisa Anderson]]. Holzer has been credited with creating the term "The Other Side" (already in use, however, in nineteenth-century spiritualism) or in full "The Other Side of Life".  He is also sometimes credited with having coined the term [[ghost hunting|ghost hunter]], which was the title of his first book on the paranormal published in 1963. However, an earlier book by [[Harry Price]] published in 1936 was titled ''Confessions of a Ghost Hunter''.

In 1970, Holzer published a study of spirit photography called ''Psychic Photography: Threshold of a New Science?''. The book included photographs taken by the spirit photographer [[John Myers (medium)|John Myers]].

Holzer believed in [[Afterlife|life after death]] and the existence of [[ghost]]s, spirits, and "stay behinds". Ghosts were, according to him, imprints left in the environment which could be "picked up" by sensitive people. Spirits were intelligent beings who could interact with the living, while "stay behinds" were those who found themselves earth-bound after death. He also believed in [[reincarnation]] and the existence of "[[Subtle body|levels of consciousness]]".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/film-obituaries/5258945/Hans-Holzer.html Hans Holzer Obituary in The Telegraph]</ref>

Holzer was a proponent of [[psychic archaeology]], which has been widely criticized as [[pseudoscience]].<ref>McKusick, Marshall. (1984). ''Psychic Archaeology from Atlantis to Oz''. ''[[Archaeology (journal)|Archaeology]]''. Vol. 37, No. 5. pp. 48-52.</ref>

Holzer was mentioned in Nathan Fielder's television show, ''[[Nathan for You]]''. A Psychic in the show claimed his mother was deemed the 'Queen of the Psychics' by Holzer himself.

Holzer and his wife Countess Catherine Geneviève [[Buxhoeveden family|Buxhoeveden]], a sixth-generation descendent of Russian Empress [[Catherine the Great]], had two daughters. The marriage was eventually dissolved.<ref name=guardobit/>

==The Amityville Horror==

Holzer's most famous investigation was into [[The Amityville Horror]] case. In January 1977, Holzer and spiritual [[Mediumship|medium]] Ethel Meyers entered [[The Amityville Horror|112 Ocean Avenue]] in [[Amityville]], New York. Meyers claimed that the house had been built over an ancient Native American burial ground and the angry spirit of a [[Shinnecock Indian Nation|Shinnecock]] Indian Chief - "Rolling Thunder" - had [[Spirit possession|possessed]] the previous occupant, [[Ronald Defeo Jr.]], driving him to murder his family. Photographs taken at the scene revealed curious anomalies such as the halos which appeared in the supposed images of bullet marks made in the original 1974 murders. Holzer's claim that the house was built on Indian sacred land was, however, denied by the local Amityville Historical Society and it was pointed out that it was the [[Montaukett]] Indians, and not the Shinnecocks, who had been the original settlers in the area. However, Indian burial sites have been found all over Long Island, including Amityville, so no one has been able to confirm or deny the burial of an Indian chief on or near the 108 Ocean Avenue property. Holzer went on to write several books about the subject, both fiction and non-fiction.

==Reception==

Holzer's endorsement of psychics in [[ghost hunting]] was criticized in an article for the ''Journal for the [[Society for Psychical Research]]'' which "cast considerable doubt on the objectivity and reliability of his work as a whole."<ref>Berger, Arthur; Berger, Joyce. (1991). ''The Encyclopedia of Parapsychology and Psychical Research''. New York: Paragon House. p. 183</ref>

Skeptical investigator [[Joe Nickell]] has written that Holzer did not provide verification for some of his claims and he credulously accepted [[Spirit photography|spirit photographs]], anecdotal reports, and other doubtful evidence.<ref>Nickell, Joe. (2000). [http://www.csicop.org/si/show/haunted_inns_tales_of_spectral_guest/ "Haunted Inns: Tales of Spectral Guest"]. ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]''. Retrieved 14 May 2016.</ref>

Nickell also wrote that the mediums Holzer endorsed Ethel Meyers and [[Sybil Leek]] offered "unsubstantiated, even unverifiable claims, or information that can be gleaned from research sources or from knowledgeable persons by “[[cold reading]]” (an artful method of fishing for information)."<ref>Nickell, Joe. (2006). [http://www.csicop.org/si/show/ghost_hunters/ "Ghost Hunters"]. ''[[Skeptical Inquirer]]''. Retrieved 14 May 2016.</ref>

Fellow ghost hunter [[Peter Underwood (parapsychologist)|Peter Underwood]] wrote an obituary for Holzer in ''[[The Guardian]]'', in which he disputed Holzer's claim (made in his 1979 book ''[[Murder in Amityville]]'') that the house on Ocean Avenue in Amityville was built on the site of a [[Shinnecock Indian Nation|Shinnecock]] burial ground.<ref name=guardobit>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/jun/18/obituary-hans-holzer|title=Hans Holzer|last=Underwood|first=Peter|date=2009-06-17|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>

Holzer's daughter, Alexandra Holzer, wrote a 2008 book titled ''Growing Up Haunted'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.schifferbooks.com/growing-up-haunted-a-ghostly-memoir-3546.html|title=Growing Up Haunted: A Ghostly Memoir - $14.95 : Schiffer Publishing|website=www.schifferbooks.com|access-date=2016-12-26}}</ref> based on her life with her father and his paranormal quest. The book was optioned by [[Marilyn Vance|Vance Entertainment]] to be developed as a potential feature film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Holzer movie|url=http://scifiandtvtalk.typepad.com/scifiandtvtalk/2013/08/growing-up-haunted-by-alexandra-holzer-optioned-as-potential-feature-film.html|publisher=SciFi Talks|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref>

